title: [IOTDB-401]Correct the calculation of a chunk if there is no data in the chunk
body:
when flushing a chunk, tsfile will calculate the size of the chunk and compare the size and the actual data size in the output stream.
When calculating the size, the chunk header is calculated (which has the measurement id and therefore the size always > 0 ). However, if we find the chunk has no data points, we do not flush anything.
In this case, the size ( >0 ) != the actual size (=0).

This PR fixes the above case.

[IOTDB-396] New query clause: disable align
body:
Disable Align Clause: DISABLE ALIGN

Rules:  
1. Both uppercase and lowercase are ok.  
Correct example: select * from root.sg1 disable align  
Correct example: select * from root.sg1 DISABLE ALIGN  

2. Disable Align Clause can only be used at the end of a query statement.  
Correct example: select * from root.sg1 where time > 10 disable align 
Wrong example: select * from root.sg1 disable align where time > 10 

3. Disable Align Clause cannot be used with Aggregation, Fill Statements, Group By or Group By Device Statements, but can with Limit Statements.
Correct example: select * from root.sg1 limit 3 offset 2 disable align
Correct example: select * from root.sg1 slimit 3 soffset 2 disable align
Wrong example: select count(s0),count(s1) from root.sg1.d1 disable align
Wrong example: select * from root.vehicle where root.vehicle.d0.s0>0 disable align
Wrong example: select * from root.vehicle group by device disable align

You could expect a table like:

title: Continue writing the last unclosed file
body:
As the TsFile close is strictly controlled in the distributed version, if a node arbitrarily closes the TsFile that is not ordered to close, the file consistency of different nodes will be broken. So during start-up, we should only close files that are confirmed to close.  

To support this, a flag is created when a file is to be closed and the flag is removed after its close is done.

title: [IOTDB-159] Fix NullPointerException in SeqTsFileRecoverTest and UnseqTsFileRecoverTest
body:
JIRA link: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/IOTDB-159

# To reproduce this bug:
The key to reproducing, is to test UnseqTsFileRecoverTest (or SeqTsFileRecoverTest) AFTER 
first testing an integration test under the test/java/org/apache/iotdb/db/integration directory, 
such as IoTDBAuthorizationIT.
```
git clone https://github.com/apache/incubator-iotdb.git
cd incubator-iotdb
mvn clean install -Dmaven.test.skip=true
cd server
mvn test -Dtest=org.apache.iotdb.db.integration.IoTDBAuthorizationIT,org.apache.iotdb.db.writelog.recover.UnseqTsFileRecoverTest
```

# The cause of this bug:
FlushSubTaskPoolManager.getInstance() is shared between IoTDBAuthorizationIT and UnseqTsFileRecoverTest. 

In the integration tests under the test/java/org/apache/iotdb/db/integration directory, tearDown() will call FlushSubTaskPoolManager.stop() and finally **set FlushSubTaskPoolManager.pool to be null**. 

In UnseqTsFileRecoverTest (or SeqTsFileRecoverTest), test() will call:
```
performer.recover()
->redoLogs(restorableTsFileIOWriter)
->new MemTableFlushTask
->subTaskPoolManager.submit(encodingTask)
```
Therefore, if UnseqTsFileRecoverTest (or SeqTsFileRecoverTest) is tested behind integration tests, it will find that **subTaskPoolManager.pool is null**. Thus, NullPointerException is thrown.

# To fix this bug:
Add `FlushSubTaskPoolManager.getInstance().start()` to setup() of SeqTsFileRecoverTest and UnseqTsFileRecoverTest. Accordingly, also add `FlushSubTaskPoolManager.getInstance().stop()` to tearDown().

title: [IOTDB-418] add some impl of NewSeriesReaderWithoutValueFilter
body:
The process of processing read data is a very complicated one, and previous read interfaces were obscure and confusing. 
I reimplemented a reader based on which all the data in the files could be queried in order

I have mainly done the following work:

1. Renamed `iAggregateReader` in `TsFile` project to `IPageSkipRader`

2. Added `IChunkReader`. Based on this interface, there are two implementations, `ChunkReader` and `MemChunkReader`

3. Added `ChunkMetadata` for `ReadonlyMemChunk` and `PageHeader` for `MemChunkReader`

4. Added `IAggregateReader` and `IRawReader` interface and `AbstractDataReader` abstract class to complete all functions of the new reader, respectively realizing `RawDataReaderWithoutValueFilter`, `SeriesDataReaderWithoutValueFilter` and `SeriesDataReaderWithValueFilter`

5. Refactoring `group by`, `raw query` and `aggregate query` ,and so on

title: Delete the duplicated fields in the BatchData class
abstract TsFileFlushPolicy and allow specifying storage groups in flush command
body:
To make the different replicas of a data partition consistent, the distributed version needs to force all replicas close file by the leader instead of on their own. So the TsFileFlushPolicy is abstracted to make this behavior controllable.

Moreover, since the leader should be able to make a follower close one of its storage group, the grammar of the flush command is enhanced to support finer granularity.

title: [IOTDB-389] Parallel Raw data query
body:
I apply the producer-consumer module and only change the NewEngineDataSetWithoutValueFilter.

Add a blocking queue that buffers a predefined(5 in this version) number of BatchDatas for each time series. Once a BatchData is produced and the blocking queue is not full, the producer submit itself to generate another task to produce for this time series before it ends itself.

The main thread also the consumer is responsible for taking from the blocking of each time series to align them. If one queue is empty, it means the data of that time series is not ready, main thread just blocked and waiting for it ready.

The performance evaluation:

In my mac, one device, ten sensors, long datatype, RLE & SNAPPY. Each time series contains 1 billion data points. Total 562M data on disk.

I query the raw data of ten time series with a time filter that results in 10, 20 and 30 millionpoints in total.

Here are the results:
(master version: 994dc325c) (multiThread version: 47a1e0c)
___________________________________________________________________________________
point number per sensor   |    master(single-thread)      |     TYMultiThread        |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10,000,000                         |                16160ms                |             10930ms          |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
20,000,000                         |               25970ms                |             20227ms          |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
30,000,000                         |               42424ms                |             30281ms          |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

It improves about 30%.

And we analyze the results, each time the main thread(consumer) to take from the queue, the queue is always full. It means that almost all time is spent on the data align.
And the analysis is supported by the JProfile results.

title: Track the merge history in TsFileResource
body:
In the assumed distributed version of IoTDB, the replicas of the same partition share the same file generation policy, that is, the file closes are controlled by the leader so all replicas will generate the same files, despite the inner structure will be a little different due to the size of memtables are different.

The greatest advantage of sharing the same file generation policy will be greatly reliving data comparison across different replicas. Just comparing the file list is enough for a node to know which data it has or not.

However, when it combines with merge, things are more complicated. Because each node has its own merge policy, after rounds of merges, file lists on different nodes will be totally different, and it will be impossible to do data comparison by file name comparison. But notice that although different nodes merge file differently, the merged files all root from the same files, which are the files generated by the flush (direct files).

Naturally, tracking the merge history by recording what direct files a file consists of will help to resolve what files are new to an IoTDB despite different merge policies.

title: [IOTDB-361]Refactor session management
body:
1. Remove uses of ThreadLocals in TSServiceImpl
2. TS_SessionHandles are replaced with sessionIds
3. TSOperationHandles are replaced with queryIds
4. Make queryId in TSServiceImpl generated by QueryResourceManager

To remove the constraint of serving each client with a separate thread, ThreadLocals in TSServiceImpl are removed. Instead, each session (connection) will be given a sessionId as the unique identifier. In every request that needs authentication, the sessionId must be passed along with to indicate who the client is.

This also fundamentally supports query management in the distributed version.

title: Change the return content in TSQueryDataSet and remove the row record in IoTDBQueryResultSet
body:
There is no need to construct a row record every time the next() function is called, we can extract the value from the corresponding value byte buffer.
Before, we use a byte size bool to indicate whether it is a null value, but the null values are rare, so the space is wasted.
Now, I use a bitmap to indicate whether it is a null value, in this way, each value only consumes extra one bit size instead of one byte size.

title: [IOTDB-334] Move LIMIT&OFFSET to Server Side
body:
Moving LIMIT&OFFSET to the server side has two benefits :-)
1. reduces the size of the result data transferred between the server and the client. In the old code, the server returns the result data starting at the first row to the client, and leaves the boring work of iterating to the OFFSET row to the client.
2. makes the code of jdbc easier to understand.


To achieve the benefits, changes in this pr include:
- The server side:
  - sql->logicalPlan->physicalPlan
    - Antlr4 doesn't need changing
    - parse LIMIT&OFFSET parameters and save them in logicalPlan (Note that SLIMIT&SOFFSET parameters are also saved in logicalOperator. SLIMIT&SOFFSET take effect in the optimization of logicalPlan or in the generation of physicalPlan from logicalPlan.)
    - pass LIMIT&OFFSET parameters from logicalPlan to physicalPlan
  - physicalPlan->QueryDataSet
    - pass LIMIT&OFFSET parameters from physicalPlan to QueryDataSet
  - QueryDataSet->fetch data
    - modify QueryDataSet's `hasNext` and `next` methods to make LIMIT&OFFSET take effect
- The client side:
  - remove the old LIMIT&OFFSET logic in the IoTDBQueryResultSet's `hasNext` and `next` methods
  - remove the  support of IoTDBStatement's `setMaxRows` and `getMaxRows` methods for the clarity and ease of maintenance of code.

title: [IOTDB-337]Add timestamp precision properties for grafana
body:
In the grafana module, timestamps are in milliseconds. In this case, when users choose "us" or "ns" in engine, it'll not work correctly. This pr is to fix this bug.

The jira link: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/IOTDB-337

title: [IOTDB-330] Improve the reading method of unsequence data
body:
Improve the reading method of unsequence data:
* Make `UnseqResourceMergeReader` implement `IBatchReader`, and use `PriorityMergeReader` as a variable instead of extending it.
* Make `PriorityMergeReader` not implement `IPointReader`, which returns Element directly instead of returning TimeValuePair
* Split TimeValuePair in `PriorityMergeReader` heap element into time and value

title: [IOTDB-336]declare that the release version of JDK is 8
body:
I tried to use JDK11 to compile a binary file, you can get it at https://dist.apache.org/repos/dist/dev/incubator/iotdb/0.8.2/rc1.

However, if a user uses JDK8 to run it, an exception will occur:

java.lang.NoSuchMethodError: java.nio.ByteBuffer.clear()Ljava/nio/ByteBuffer;

 

It is because before JDK9, ByteBuffer.clear() returns  Buffer, while from JDK9 on, the method return ByteBuffer.

 

According to https://github.com/apache/curator/pull/312, add a parameter `release 8` can solve the problem. 

In maven, we can add a property called 

```

<maven.compiler.release>8</maven.compiler.release>

```

title: [IOTDB-306] new reader with ChunkMetaData for aggregateFunction
body:
In the old interface, data filtering could not be use the chunk level, which I think may not have been considered in the previous design. Now the IAggregateReader interface has been added `hasNextChunk`  `nextChunkMeta` `hasNextPageInCurrentChunk`.

The advantage of this is that Statistics can be used in the AggrFunction, there is no need to read page

This some test, **i restart the server after each kind of test**:

1. 10,000 data without chunkMeta and unseq
IoTDB> `select count(*) from root`
It costs 0.290s
IoTDB> `select first_value(*) from root`
It costs 0.657s
IoTDB> `select last_value(*) from root`
It costs 0.156s
IoTDB> `select sum(*) from root`
It costs 0.224s
IoTDB> `select avg(*) from root`
It costs 0.272s
IoTDB> `select max_time(*) from root`
It costs 0.117s

1. 10,000 data with chunkMeta but without unseq
IoTDB>  `select count(*) from root`
It costs 0.006s
IoTDB> `select first_value(*) from root`
It costs 0.006s
IoTDB> `select sum(*) from root`
It costs 0.005s
IoTDB> `select avg(*) from root`
It costs 0.006s
IoTDB> `select max_time(*) from root`
It costs 0.004s
